<br>
No secret, used to be in the program myself, and every server had a father GM. Cant remember when, but it was a month before I quit the program, our father GMs were stripped from us and we were given a GM &quot;Team&quot;, 2 of each specialized in certain fields. Quests, name policies, etc.<br>
<br>
The entire idea, in theory, was to provide more coverage to the playerbase. WIth more GMs to each server, you get more help. Unfortunatly, not only did the idea not even seem to work in theory (as communism does), it completely backfired on SOE.<br>
<br>
We (guides) starting leaving the program in record numbers. We no longer had a father figure (and the guides on every server are VERY close with each other) and now our &quot;go-to&quot; person was, in all honesty, a very rude, arrogant stranger. actually...MANY rude arrogant strangers. <br>
<br>
So, first off, when the guides started leaving, the playerbase lost its second level assistance. There were (and are) no guides online to assist with rezzes, etc. <br>
<br>
Second, with the lack of guides, thats more work for the SWAT. (SWAT are GM level guides who are basically called in to assist with high priority petitions). The amount of work for the SWAT was increased greatly, and was not what they were used to. Also, SWAT are not paid, as GMs are. So the SWAT started leaving. <br>
<br>
Third, with no basic coverage, and the SWAT leaving, GMs are quite busy, so they arent around online, in game, or in chat for any existing guides (or players for that matter) to go to in order to get assistance with that rez you needed, or that stuck corpse.<br>
<br>
Fourth, part of this theory is that it would be easier for the players to email their problems instead of petitioning. So the default way to get assistance was to email someone. Now, its obvious thats a candycoated of the real reason because nobody wants to log OUT of game to get help when people should be IN GAME to help. The real reason is simply laziness, lack of coverage, and VI's realization of the lack of coverage.<br>
<br>
Fifth, and in addition to the lack of basic level guides, you have nobody to train to new apprentices, so when &quot;Training times&quot; are being emailed to the applicants, they either arent showing up, or there is no trainer online when they should be, or no GM available to buff.<br>
<br>
So there you have it, folks. The entire nutshell. Thats the very problem, and its cause, that we are suffering from today. for the next week, do a who all gm, You will see Vaerus, who is a 3 month guide, you will see THreklyvair, who is still in his guide apprenticeship, and you will see one other. Pay homage to Vaerus, and scold yourself for flaming Vaylin and Adoner.<br>
